idCitation.resTitle: Upper Claiborne Aquifer: Alabama, Arkansas, Louisiana, Missouri, Mississippi, Tennessee 2006-2008

dataIdInfo.idAbs: Outcrop and subcrop extent of the Upper Claiborne Aquifer in Arkansas, Alabama, Louisiana, Missouri, Mississippi, and Tennessee. The hydrogeologic unit dataset contains 414 rows and 394 columns representing 1-mile grid spacing. In general, limitations of data interpolation included areas of sparse geophysical log control points, log datums not clearly defined for some logs, unknown exact extent of each hydrogeologic unit in subcrop, interpolation limitations, and values averaged over 1-mile grid spacing.
dataIdInfo.idPurp: The purpose of these data is to provide a digital map of the surface of select hydrogeologic units in the Mississippi embayment aquifer system.
dataIdInfo.idCredit: Jeff Brantly and Ron Seanor, USGS Louisiana Water Science Center, Mike Bradley and Jack Carmichael, USGS Tennessee Water Science Center, Heather Welch, Jeannie Barlow, and Claire Rose, USGS Mississippi Water Science Center, Lafayette and Rolla Publishing Service Centers

report.measDesc: No formal logical accuracy tests were conducted.

The interpolated digital hydrogeologic surface covers the extent to which the presumed extent of the hydrogeologic unit in subcrop exits, and therefore, covers the extent at which the geophysical log control points exist. Data set is considered complete for the information presented, as described in the abstract. Users are advised to read the rest of the metadata record carefully for additional details.

The correlation altitude on the geophysical logs and the altitude of the interpolated digital hydrogeologic surface was determined at every location a geophysical log control point existed. The differences between the geophysical log control point and the interpolated digital hydrogeologic surface at each location represents how accurate the interpolated digital hydrogeologic surface is to the "real world" geophysical log control point. Mean differences (correlation altitude on the geophysical logs minus interpolated digital hydrogeologic surface altitude) is the average difference between the unit correlation altitudes on the geophysical logs and the altitudes of the interpolated digital hydrogeologic surfaces at the location of the geophysical log control point. Minimum and maximum differences are those measured between the unit correlation altitudes on the geophysical logs and the altitudes of the interpolated digital hydrogeologic surfaces; absolute mean error is the error between the unit correlation altitudes on the geophysical logs and the altitudes of the interpolated digital hydrogeologis surfaces.
A formal accuracy assessment of the horizontal positional information in the data set has not been conducted.
A formal accuracy assessment of the vertical positional information in the data set has either not been conducted, or is not applicable.
